(94, 'The patch test, skin prick test, and serum milk-specific IgE as diagnostic tools in cow''s milk allergy in infants', 'T. Vanto K. Juntunen-Backman K. Kalimo T. Klemola,A. Koivikko', 'We evaluated the value of the patch test, skin prick test, and\nHospital, Skin and Allergy Hospital, Department milk-specific IgE by CAP RAST in 301 infants with suspected\nof Allergology, Helsinki hypersensitivity to cow''s milk. The patch test was carried out\nK. Kalimo, Department of Dermatology, Turku\nUniversity Hospital, Turku\nwith milk powder, and the skin prick test with cow''s milk-based\nP. Koskinen, Central Laboratory, Turku formula. Hypersensitivity to cow''s milk was determined with\nUniversity Hospital, Turku, Finland double-blind, placebo-controlled challenge. An immediate reac-\nCorrespondence to:\ntion to cow''s milk challenge was observed in 100 infants (33%),\nTimo Vanto, MD, Dr.Med.Sci. a delayed reaction in 76 (25%), and a negative result in 125\nDepartment of Pediatrics (42%). Skin prick test wheals were significantly greater in infants\nTurku University Hospital with immediate reactions than in infants with delayed or\nFIN-20520 Turku\nFinland\nnegative reactions. Milk-specific IgE was correlated with the\nskin prick test (r=0.78, P,0.001, n=268) but did not contribute\nto further discrimination of immediate reactions from delayed\nor negative reactions compared to skin prick test alone. In our\nstudy population, the skin prick test (diameter $3 mm) showed\na specificity and sensitivity of 91% and 69%; the results for\nmilk-specific IgE ($0.7 kU/l) were 88% and 58%, respectively.\nThe patch test did not distinguish subjects with immediate or\ndelayed reactions from those with negative reactions.', 'a:91:{i:1;s:1:"*";i:4;s:6:"jurnal";i:8;s:1:"-";i:9;s:5:"judul";i:10;d:0.29999999999999999;i:11;s:2:"*j";i:12;s:6:"juduls";i:13;s:2:"-j";i:14;d:0.10000000000000001;i:15;s:4:"milk";i:16;s:2:"-j";i:17;d:0.10000000000000001;i:18;s:4:"test";i:19;s:2:"-j";i:20;d:0.1000